China - Infectious Disease causing delays in Hubei Province
Last updated today at 7:00
China Post has informed us that as advised by their Government, measures have been taken to prevent the risk of further transmission and spreading of the novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV) by disinfecting all parcels destined to or transiting via Wuhan at its processing centres. In an effort to keep delivery channels open to Hubei province (postcodes 430000â€“449999), China Post will contact the addressee by telephone before delivery to ask about their delivery preferences. The parcels can either be temporarily stored at the postal outlet, or made available for pick-up from the outlet, or delivered to a smart parcel locker, or delivered by other non-face-to-face methods. Delivery methods for international parcels are thus agreed by the recipient before delivery.Please note that it will also not be possible to provide written proof of delivery in some cases.These attempts to limit the spreading of 2019-nCoV will unfortunately result in some delivery delays for our globalpriority and globalvalue products.In respect of globalexpress services, parcel services have been suspended for the Wuhan region since 23 January.Please note, parcels services remain open to China and the above measures from China Post are currently ensuring that there is no suspension of service.Further updates will be provided here daily or whenever more detail is made available.
